value.value: A cellular process phenotype in which premeiotic DNA replication does not occur.
A cell phenotype in which cells show decreased sensitivity to heat shock. Heat shock is a form of heat stress in which cells are briefly exposed to a very high temperature.

A phenotype in which cells in a population show decreased sensitivity to a stress. Typically, a cell population is deemed resistant to a stress if cells in the population grow and divide when exposed to the stress at an intensity at which wild-type cells stop growing (and may die).

definition.value: This is a high-level term whose primary purpose is to organize terms beneath it in the ontology, and we expect that it will not be used for direct annotations. Please consider using a more specific term to annotate each phenotype. Use a descendant of this term if you have assayed growth of cells exposed to a stress in culture. If you have assayed the response to the stress at the subcellular or molecular level, consider annotating to a descendant of 'abnormal cellular response to stress' (FYPO:0000162).

label.value: resistance to heat shock during nitrogen starvation

value.value: A cell phenotype in which cells show decreased sensitivity to heat shock, when the cell is also subject to nitrogen starvation. Heat shock is a form of heat stress in which cells are briefly exposed to a very high temperature.

definition.value: This term can be used for any circumstances in which cells are starved for nitrogen. Note that cells may enter G0 (quiescence) when subjected to prolonged nitrogen starvation; this term is not restricted to G0.

label.value: normal cell morphology during nitrogen starvation

value.value: A cell phenotype characterized by normal cell morphology (i.e. size, shape, and structure indistinguishable from wild type) when the cell is subject to nitrogen starvation. Wild-type cells become spherical upon nitrogen starvation, and have a smaller volume than under nitrogen-replete conditions.

definition.value: This term can be used for any circumstances in which cells are starved for nitrogen. Note that cells may enter G0 (quiescence) when subjected to prolonged nitrogen starvation; this term is not restricted to G0.

value.value: A cell morphology phenotype in which a vegetative cell is elongated, has no septum, and contains more than one nucleus.

label.value: branched elongated multinucleate aseptate vegetative cell

value.value: A cell morphology phenotype in which vegetative a cell is branched, elongated, has no septum, and contains more than one nucleus.

label.value: swollen elongated multinucleate aseptate vegetative cell

value.value: A cell morphology phenotype in which a vegetative cell is swollen, elongated, has no septum, and contains more than one nucleus. In a swollen cell, both length and diameter may be greater than normal, although the cell is only considered elongated if the length:diameter ratio is also greater than normal.
A cell population phenotype in which the frequency of occurrence of ascospore formation is normal (i.e. indistinguishable from wild type).
A molecular function phenotype in which the observed rate of DNA topoisomerase II activity is normal (i.e. indistinguishable from wild type).
A cellular process phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which the occurrence of mitochondrial translation is decreased.

definition.value: Note that this term should be used only when an experiment measures mitochondrial protein synthesis directly, e.g. by measuring incorporation of a radiolabeled amino acid. Consider annotating to 'decreased protein level' (FYPO:0000835) or one of its descendants.

value.value: A cell population phenotype that reflects the proportion of the population that survive and develop normally.

definition.value: This is a high-level term whose primary purpose is to organize terms beneath it in the ontology, and we expect that it will not be used for direct annotations. Please consider using a more specific term to annotate each phenotype.

value.value: A cell population phenotype in which cells in the population are viable.

definition.value: Note that a viable population may contain individual cells that are inviable. Usually it is difficult to detect inviable cells within an otherwise viable population, especially if population growth is simply assayed by OD increase in liquid culture or by colony formation on plates. If you have done an experiment that detects individual inviable cells, consider using the term 'mixed population including viable and inviable cells' (FYPO:0000908).

value.value: A cell population phenotype in which none of the cells in the population are viable.
A cell population phenotype in which cells in the population are viable in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle.
A cell population phenotype in which all cells in the population are inviable in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle.

A cellular process phenotype in which the growth of a cell is normal (i.e. indistinguishable from wild type). Cell growth is the process in which a cell irreversibly increases in size over time by accretion and biosynthetic production of matter similar to that already present.

definition.value: Note that this term refers to growth at the level of any individual cell, and that it specifies only that increase in cell size due to metabolism is normal. Other aspects of the cell's biology may be abnormal, and other abnormalities may affect increase in cell number (population growth). Also see 'cell population growth phenotype' (FYPO:0000139) and its descendants.

value.value: A molecular function phenotype in which the observed rate of a 3'-5'-exoribonuclease activity is abnormal.
A molecular function phenotype in which a 3'-5'-exoribonuclease activity is absent.
A molecular function phenotype in which the observed rate of a 3'-5'-exoribonuclease activity is normal (i.e. indistinguishable from wild type).
A cell phenotype in which a cell has no septum, is elongated, and is inviable.

definition.value: Note that if you have done an experiment that assays the viability of a population of cells, such as looking at colony growth or growth in liquid culture, you should also annotate to 'inviable cell population' (FYPO:0002059) or one of its descendants.

label.value: slow cell population growth during recovery from stationary phase

value.value: A cell population phenotype in which a cell population grows more slowly than normal when the population has been in stationary phase and is then placed in conditions that allow recovery.
Auxotrophy in which a cell is unable to synthesize histidine, and therefore requires histidine in the medium for vegetative cell growth.
A physical cellular phenotype in which a cell has a nucleus in an abnormal location. The normal location is at the midpoint of the long axis of the cell.
A physical cellular phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which a cell has a nucleus in the normal location at the midpoint of the long axis of the cell.

A physical cellular phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which a cell has a nucleus in an abnormal location. The normal location of a single nucleus is at the midpoint of the long axis of the cell (during mitotic telophase, daughter nuclei normally move away from the cell division site).
A physical cellular phenotype in which a prospore has a nucleus in an abnormal location. The normal location is at the midpoint of the long axis of the cell.

label.value: protein mislocalized to nucleus during cellular response to copper ion

value.value: A cell phenotype in which a protein that is not normally found in the nucleus is observed there during a cellular response to copper ions.

definition.value: Note that this term can be used to annotate any case where a protein is found in the nucleus in a mutant, but not in wild type. In some cases, there may be enough additional information to annotate to 'abnormal protein localization' (FYPO:0000443) or one of its descendants. We recommend noting which protein(s) were used in the assay when annotating to this term.

label.value: inviable elongated cell with fragmented nucleus and increased septum thickness

value.value: A cell phenotype in which a cell is elongated, has a nucleus that is broken into multiple small fragments, forms a septum that is thicker than normal, and is inviable.

definition.value: Note that if you have done an experiment that assays the viability of a population of cells, such as looking at colony growth or growth in liquid culture, you should also annotate to 'inviable cell population' (FYPO:0002059) or one of its descendants.

value.value: A cell phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which cells show increased sensitivity to conditions of low osmolarity.

label.value: sensitive to calcium during cellular hypotonic response

value.value: A phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which cells show increased sensitivity to calcium during a cellular hypotonic response. Cells stop growing (and may die) at a concentration of calcium ions that allows wild type cells to grow.

label.value: normal growth on calcium during cellular hypotonic response

value.value: A phenotype in which vegetative cell population growth is normal (i.e. indistinguishable from wild type) in a medium containing calcium ions during a cellular hypotonic response.

A phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which cells show increased sensitivity to N-tosyl-L-phenylalanyl chloromethyl ketone (TPCK). Cells stop growing (and may die) at a concentration of TPCK that allows wild type cells to grow.
A phenotype in which vegetative cell population growth is normal (i.e. indistinguishable from wild type) in a medium containing N-tosyl-L-phenylalanyl chloromethyl ketone (TPCK).

label.value: increased protein ubiquitination during vegetative growth

value.value: A cellular process phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which the occurrence of ubiquitination of one or more specific proteins, or of specific protein sites, is increased.

definition.value: Consider also annotating to 'increased level of ubiquitinated protein in cell during vegetative growth' (FYPO:0002774). We recommend noting which protein(s) were used in the assay when annotating to this term.

label.value: inviable swollen elongated cell with enlarged nucleus

value.value: A cell morphology phenotype in which a vegetative cell is inviable, is swollen, is elongated, and in which the nucleus is larger than normal. The cell contains one nucleus and no septum. In a swollen cell, both length and diameter may be greater than normal, although the cell is only considered elongated if the length:diameter ratio is also greater than normal.

definition.value: The distinction between this phenotype and centrally constricted (dumbbell-shaped) cells (FYPO:0000779) is that swollen elongated cells do not have a constriction along the long axis. Swollen elongated cells may have a uniform diameter, or may be swollen only around the nucleus. This phenotype is usually seen in diploid cells, so consider also annotating to 'increased spontaneous diploidization' (FYPO:0000252).

value.value: A cell morphology phenotype in which a vegetative cell has a larger volume and cell diameter, but shorter cell length, than normal.

A cellular process phenotype in which the growth of a cell is normal (i.e. indistinguishable from wild type) in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle. Cell growth is the process in which a cell irreversibly increases in size over time by accretion and biosynthetic production of matter similar to that already present.

definition.value: Note that this term refers to growth at the level of any individual cell, and that it specifies only that increase in cell size due to metabolism is normal. Other aspects of the cell's biology may be abnormal, and other abnormalities may affect increase in cell number (population growth). Also see 'cell population growth phenotype' (FYPO:0000139) and its descendants.

label.value: exocytic vesicles present in increased numbers

value.value: A physical cellular phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which cells contain more exocytic vesicles than normal.

label.value: exocytic vesicles present in increased numbers at cell tip during mitotic interphase

value.value: A physical cellular phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which cells contain more exocytic vesicles at one or both cell tips than normal during interphase of the mitotic cell cycle, when the cell is growing.

label.value: exocytic vesicles present in increased numbers at septum during septum assembly

value.value: A physical cellular phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which cells contain more exocytic vesicles than normal near the division septum while the cell is undergoing septum assembly.

A cellular process phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which exocytosis is abnormal. Exocytosis is the release of intracellular molecules (e.g. hormones, matrix proteins) contained within a membrane-bounded vesicle by fusion of the vesicle with the plasma membrane of a cell. A phenotype may affect exocytosis of all cargoes, or of specific cargo such as a particular protein.

A cellular process phenotype in which homologous chromosomes or sister chromatids do not move towards the spindle poles at the same time during nuclear division, but instead one or more chromosomes remain distant from the spindle pole after the bulk of the DNA has separated. Segregation may stop before completing separation of chromosomes, or may eventually be completed.

definition.value: Chromosome lagging may reflect a delay in detachment of homologous chromosomes or sister chromatids from each other ('chromosome separation' as defined by GO:0051304), polewards movement (GO:0051305), or both.

value.value: A cellular process phenotype in which homologous chromosomes or sister chromatids do not move towards the spindle poles at the same time during meiosis I or meiosis II, but instead one or more chromosomes remain distant from the spindle pole after the bulk of the DNA has separated. Segregation may stop before completing separation of chromosomes, or may eventually be completed.

definition.value: Chromosome lagging may reflect a delay in detachment of homologous chromosomes or sister chromatids from each other ('chromosome separation' as defined by GO:0051307), polewards movement (GO:0016344), or both.

value.value: A cellular process phenotype in which cohesion between sister chromatids is abnormal during meiosis.
A cellular process phenotype in which cohesion between sister chromatids is decreased during meiosis.

definition.value: Abnormal cohesion may cause separation of sister chromatids during the first meiotic nuclear division, leading to equational segregation. If this occurs, also annotate to 'equational sister chromatid separation during meiosis I' (FYPO:0005634).

value.value: A cellular process phenotype in which cohesion between sister chromatids is normal (i.e. indistinguishable from wild type) during meiosis.

label.value: increased protein phosphorylation during cellular response to DNA damage

value.value: A cellular process phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which the phosphorylation of one or more specific proteins, or of specific protein sites, occurs to a greater extent than normal during a cellular response to a DNA damage stimulus.

definition.value: We recommend noting which protein(s) were used in the assay when annotating to this term.

label.value: increased protein phosphorylation during cellular response to hydroxyurea

value.value: A cellular process phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which the phosphorylation of one or more specific proteins, or of specific protein sites, occurs to a greater extent than normal during a cellular response to hydroxyurea.

definition.value: Also consider annotating to 'increased protein phosphorylation during cellular response to DNA damage' (FYPO:0002095). When using this term, it is recommended to note the specific protein(s) affected.

label.value: decreased protein kinase activity during cellular response to hydroxyurea

value.value: A molecular function phenotype in which the observed rate of a protein kinase activity is decreased during a cellular response to hydroxyurea.
